What I Genuinely Dislike
The code duplication is inexcusable for a project of this ambition. 14 copies of safe_float() is not engineering. It's prototyping that was never cleaned up.

49 pages is feature-stuffing, not product design. You built everything you could think of instead of ruthlessly cutting to what matters. The result feels like a developer's toy, not an executive tool.

No pre-computed data layer. Every page load hits ACCOUNT_USAGE with complex queries. This will cost real money and perform poorly at scale. A senior architect would have built a data mart layer first.

The "Ask OVERWATCH" feature is a gimmick. Context-stuffing session state into a Cortex COMPLETE call with an 8000-char limit produces shallow answers. It will disappoint users after the first "wow" moment. Either build it properly with Cortex Agent + tool-use, or remove it.

Tests are effectively non-existent. The test file is corrupted (multiple classes concatenated without proper file boundaries). There is no CI. This is not production-ready by any enterprise standard.

The architecture is monolithic. 50 Python files in a single Streamlit app means one bug in any section can crash the entire dashboard. There's no isolation, no error boundary per section, no graceful page-level failure.

